        The Weeknd did wonders with new album release as he have 6 songs on TOP 100 this week including 3 songs inside the TOP 40. Despite that he was lucky to have "Sacrifice" peaked inside the TOP 10 at #10 (was #06 on midweeks but barely make it TOP 10 as sales and streams keep dropping).

His new single "Gasoline" may get into the charts next week as it's #55 on Spotify (but is not on iTunes TOP 100 right now).

        WEEKLY CHART REVIEW (14/01/2022 20/01/2022)

        (Negative)

        1) We Dont Talk Bruno climbs into third position! This is meant to be the huge breakthrough hit for Encanto & I honestly dont get why. It doesnt have the same anthemic swell like previous soundtrack hits in the charts like Let It Go or This Is Me, for example. Granted, I cant really comment on the content in context with the film (purely because I havent seen it yet), but unfortunately, no member of the cast here seems to stand out to me either! Yeah, sorry, I appreciate Lin-Manuel Mirandas writing a lot (especially over Latin production), but this song feels incredibly boring & dreary as a whole.

        2) Pushin P made it in! I mean, come on, it doesnt even sound any of three rappers in question are trying. I couldnt even make out what they were saying because of how mumbled & autotuned they all sound, not to mention how terribly the production is mixed into it! Theres at least some kind of alliteration going on here, the bass groove is okay & some of the lyrics are just so cringewortby that theyre actually kind of laughable, but no, even those things arent enough to save this from being a sloppily produced mess.

        (Mixed)

        1) ABCDEFU finally took the #1 despite narrowly missing out last week! This song seems to be one thats divided opinion across the community & even with all of that, Im still not sure where I sit on it. Sure, the writing is incredibly basic & the rollicking guitar that opens the song along with Gayles bitter delivery kind of reminds me of Hot Girl Bummer! That being said, this is at least a little bit better because of the sudden swell of anger in the hook where Gayle is just done trying to be patient with an ex thats treating her horribly & remember that shes only 17 at the end of the day. Overall, this is fine enough, but given how much its getting overplayed & the insane competition coming from break-up songs now, Im not sure how well this is going to end up aging for me!

        2) Fingers Crossed took a massive jump as everybody predicted! Funnily enough, the first thing I heard about this song were immediate comparisons to Drivers License & is it just me, or is there very little resemblance between the two songs at all? For one, Lauren is taking a much more acoustic approach to this with the instrumentation, particularly in the verses, but I find her vocals to be a lot throatier & sometimes even more rough, especially in the hook! I guess while its a good sign that her voice doesnt crack beneath all the raw power shes driving into that chorus, it also limits the vocal range that shes truly capable of reaching, which is probably why I prefer the breathier delivery towards the end of the song. Another thing to note is the content, because while it was clear that Rodrigo still has feelings after parting ways from a former lover, Spencer-Smith is very dismissive of the guy in question & absolutely wants nothing more to do with him! So yeah, this certainly isnt bad & I completely get why new single people would turn to it, but at the same time, I dont think this is going to be the career-defining moment for the upcoming teenager unlike what we were seeing exactly a year ago around now, thats all Im saying.

        3) Surface Pressure breaks into the Top 10! See, this is the kind of track from the Encanto soundtrack that sounds like it has a lot more long-term potential. Funnily enough, the vocals range from Lizzo in the first verse to Katy Perry in the hook, but I still feel that Jessica Darrow is sticking too much to her lower range & this really couldve had a lot more potential if she pushed for those power notes instead! Mind you, I think the larger issue here is the backing band not really showing any sense of real dynamic whatsoever, which youd think a song that addresses the pressures of anxiety & stress kind of effective to have. Again, I probably like this more than any other song from the film at least out of those charting, but this should still be a lot better in my opinion!

        4) Retail Therapy making its debut! Ive never been one to get on board with Central Cee due to his lack of hype & limited flow, but neither of those seem to be much of a problem here at all. Yeah, I think he rides the beat fairly well, the percussion touches to this sound really pristine & the drill bass hits at just the right time! Im still not fully sold on the sped-up sample of Hank Crawfords Wildflower just yet & the lyrics are ultimately just Central Cee bragging about his extensive clothing range, but for his usual standards, this ranks above average for me. Maybe itll grow on me even more with a few additional listens?

        5) Miserable Man hits the Top 40! Okay, I think one thing I have to commend with this is David Kushner himself. His deeper vocals to really hone in on the story-telling of how hes overcome his troubles by moving to a new home with his family & all the anguish he looks back on kind of gives me stripped-back Hozier vibes. The echoey background vocals might make this all the more sombre, but theyre also a fitting accompaniment, especially as the song comes to a close! Heck, even the guitar swipes over a fairly simple melody dont really bother me as much as they normally would for a song in this lane. So whats holding this back for me? Probably the fact that its dragged out for way longer than it needs to be, especially with the outro, it wouldve been a much better climax to finish off with a final verse or something, but hey, if any song Im covering today has potential to be upgraded to the positive section, its this one!

        6) Make Me Feel Good held up better than I expected! This seems to be going more for the retro disco vibe in literally every single aspect, so Im entirely on board with how much it stands out from the other dance hits in the chart, but even as a lifelong EDM lover, I cant help that feel that this is way too repetitive to properly get into it.

        (Positive)

        1) Ive now given my scores for The Weeknds new album in another post, but lets just say that Im absolutely delighted about him getting the #1 album with Dawn FM, especially when some of the highlights from it like Sacrifice & How Do I Make You Love Me? are both here, but Less Than Zero joining them really wouldve been the icing on the cake!

        2) Where Are You Now moved into the Top 20! I was kind of worried that the UK would just sleep on this when it was taking off over Europe last autumn, but Im so glad that they didnt.

        3) Down Under is holding up relatively well! Im usually kind of mixed on drum & bass music as a whole, but this took a classic rock hit from the 80s & somehow didnt ruin it! That has to be worth something, haha.

        Thanks for reading everyone! Glad to be bringing these weekly reviews back here yet again. :)
